High-Intensity Discharge (HID) lights are categorized into several types such as Metal Halide Lamps, High-Pressure Sodium Lamps, Xenon Lamps, and Mercury Lamps. Metal Halide Lamps are widely used for outdoor and warehouse lighting due to their bright white light. High-Pressure Sodium Lamps are commonly used for roadway lighting as they have high luminous efficacy. Xenon Lamps, known for their bright output and long lifespan, find applications in automotive headlights. Mercury Lamps, though less popular due to environmental concerns, are still used in industrial settings where high-intensity lighting is required. In terms of applications, HID lights are extensively utilized in automotive headlights, roadway lighting, warehouse lighting, stadium lighting, and various other sectors. The automotive sector is a major consumer of HID lights, especially for automotive headlights. Construction, sports & entertainment, and industrial sectors also heavily rely on HID lights for their lighting requirements.

